         </item-info>
         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="f0005">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0005">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">The location of the research area (a) and conceptual diagram of the natural restoration stage (b).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr1" id="lk00005"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0010">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Differences in species composition among SC, SG, and OG stages. Marginal boxplot illustrating inter-group differences on the first and second axis in NMDS. The significant difference was denoted by lowercase letters.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr2" id="lk00010"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0015">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0025" view="all">Differences in local contribution to beta diversity (LCBD) among SC, SG, and OG. The significance is denoted by different lowercase letters.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr3" id="lk00015"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0020">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">Ternary diagram for comparing components of beta diversity among stages of natural restoration. The horizontal axis represents the proportion of nestedness, while the upper left and upper right axes represent the proportions of turnover and similarity, respectively. Each point represents a pair of FDPs, and its position is determined by the relative sizes of similarity, turnover, and nestedness, with each triplet summing to 1. The average values of similarity, turnover, and nestedness are shown under the ternary diagram. The right boxplots from top to bottom display the differences in similarity, turnover, and nestedness between stages of natural restoration. Significance differences are indicated by different lowercase letters.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr4" id="lk00020"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0025">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0035" view="all">Comparison between empirical SIMPER (red lines) and 95% confidence intervals of three null SIMPER distributions in SC-SG stage (a) and SG-OG stage (c). The green shadow indicated the 95% confidence interval of null model based on niche-assembly process, while the orange shadow indicated that based on dispersal-assembly process. The blue one represented the null model based on combined processes of both dispersal- and niche-assembly processes. Figure (b) and Figure (d) represented the E-metric distribution in SC-SG stage and SG-OG stage, respectively.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr5" id="lk00025"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0030">
               <ce:label>Fig. 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0040" view="all">Contributions of soil nutrient factors and topographic factors to LCBD. (a) The blue circle indicated the how the soil nutrient factors influenced the LCBD, while the pink circle indicated that of topographical factors. Figure (b) showed the relative importance of topographical factors on LCBD based on the random forest model. Variables with dark blue indicated significant effect (*p &lt; 0.05), while those with gray indicated no significance. The higher the %IncMSE value was, the more important the variable acted.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr6" id="lk00030"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0035">
               <ce:label>Fig. 7</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0045" view="all">The relationship between profile curvature, roughness and LCBD. The black filled circles represent the values of the test FDPs. The blue solid line represents the significant results of the correlation analysis. The gray shaded area represents the 95% confidence interval.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr7" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0341816224004211/gr7" id="lk00035"/>
            </ce:figure>
