         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="s0005" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0025" view="all">Understanding biodiversity is an essential issue in the natural sciences. However, increasing human disturbance has accelerated habitat loss or fragmentation, leading to a rapid loss of biodiversity and a critical biodiversity conservation situation (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0280 b0300" id="r0005">Poorter et al., 2023; Rehm et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>). An inadequate understanding of biodiversity patterns limits conservation efforts due to a lack of basic support, emphasizing the urgency of elucidating the biodiversity patterns and the underlying processes during restoration. At different scales, α-diversity is commonly used to characterize the biodiversity at the local scale, while γ-diversity is employed to assess biodiversity at the regional scale (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0365" id="c0085">Wu et al., 2021a</ce:cross-ref>). As a crucial link between α-diversity and γ-diversity, β-diversity can reflect the variation of species along a given gradient. Previous researches also indicated that β-diversity might involve variations in species composition among communities due to various uncertain factors (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0370 b0010" id="r0010">Wu et al., 2022a; Anderson et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>). Since β-diversity links local biodiversity (α-diversity) and the regional species pool (γ-diversity), it becomes an effective tool for understanding the variation mechanisms in biodiversity drivers (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0150 b0180 b0235 b0375" id="r0015">Geng et al., 2022; He et al., 2022; Mori et al., 2018; Wu et al., 2022b</ce:cross-refs>). An increasing number of studies showed that changes in species richness were not always associated with changes in species composition, emphasizing the asynchronous trends in species richness and species composition (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0040 b0120 b0190" id="r0020">Blowes et al., 2019; Dornelas et al., 2019; Hillebrand et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>). For example, both <ce:cross-ref refid="b0185" id="c0090">Hendershot (2020)</ce:cross-ref> and Lindholm (2021) found that species composition varied over time while species richness remained stable, suggesting that β-diversity, as complementary of variations in species α-diversity, could more intuitively reflect the temporal dynamics of biodiversity. Determining β-diversity can well extend our current understanding of biodiversity patterns and underlying processes (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0220 b0405" id="r0025">Lindholm et al., 2021; Yao et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">In order to more accurately assess the β-diversity patterns and the underlying mechanisms behind it, previous studies have proposed decomposing β-diversity into different components, such as turnover (or species replacement) and nestedness (or species richness difference) (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0025 b0210 b0270" id="r0030">Baselga, 2010; Legendre, 2014; Podani and Schmera, 2011</ce:cross-refs>). If some species are replaced by others, and this process does not alter species richness, then the change in β-diversity is a result of turnover. If forest dynamic plots (FDPs) with fewer species are subsets of species-rich FDPs, the change in β-diversity is driven by nestedness, reflecting a non-random process of species loss. Identifying the components of β-diversity can provide a good insight into the potential ecological processes shaping biodiversity patterns (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0035" id="c0095">Baselga and Leprieur, 2015</ce:cross-ref>). For example, species turnover can well reflect environmental filtering and dispersal limitation (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0255 b0370" id="r0035">Peláez and Pavanelli, 2019; Wu et al., 2022a</ce:cross-refs>), and nestedness is usually related to patterns of species colonization and extinction (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0090 b0140 b0320" id="r0040">Da Silva et al., 2018; Fontana et al., 2020; Soininen et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>). Therefore, decomposing β-diversity into turnover and nestedness, and quantifying relative variations, is crucial for further understanding biodiversity patterns and community assembly rules (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0440" id="c0100">Zhou et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">However, quantifying potential community assembly rules from observed species diversity patterns is a challenge because different underlying ecological processes may lead to the same pattern (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0005" id="c0105">Adler et al., 2007</ce:cross-ref>). Currently, the community assembly can be explained from two main perspectives. The niche-based assembly framework, which emphasizes the deterministic processes, suggests that niche differentiation is a prerequisite for species coexistence in a community, where environmental filtering and limiting similarities determine the species composition (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0165" id="c0110">Gilbert et al., 2004</ce:cross-ref>). However, the neutral theory suggests that dispersal limitation plays a decisive role in community structure, with a closer geographic distance between plant communities indicating a more similar species composition (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0140" id="c0115">Fontana et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). Existing studies showed that the actual community is subjected to the combined effects of deterministic and stochastic processes (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0170 b0245 b0335 b0360" id="r0045">Gravel et al., 2006; Ovaskainen et al., 2017; Vergnon et al., 2009; Weiher et al., 2011</ce:cross-refs>). In the niche-based assembly framework, soil nutrients and topographic factors have been shown to play important roles in forming forest community structures at the local scale (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0020 b0285 b0290" id="r0050">Baldeck et al., 2013; Punchi-Manage et al., 2013; Qiao et al., 2015</ce:cross-refs>). Specifically, soil nutrients are an essential resource for plant communities and significantly influence the species composition of the community (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0400" id="c0120">Yang et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). In contrast, topographic factors regulate several factors affecting plant growth and survival, such as light availability, microclimate, and soil nutrients (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0060 b0145" id="r0055">Chadwick and Asner, 2016; Fortunel et al., 2018</ce:cross-refs>). Changes in soil nutrients and topographic factors inevitably lead to changes in the species composition (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0200" id="c0125">Hou and Fu, 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Currently, the majority of studies have overlooked the contributions of the two components of β-diversity, leading to misunderstandings of the driving factors behind diversity pattern changes (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0195 b0370 b0440" id="r0060">Hirao et al., 2015; Wu et al., 2022a; Zhou et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Due to the combined influence of niche and stochastic processes on communities, determining the relative importance of niche and neutral processes has become a pressing key issue to address. Furthermore, the relative importance of soil nutrients and topographic factors in driving β-diversity patterns within extreme habitats are still lacking.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Karst forests provide a good example for addressing the aforementioned issues. Karst is a widely distributed geological landscape type in the world, accounting for about 6 % of China’s land area, with an important position in the southwestern region. Guizhou Province is a typical representative of China’s karst plateau (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0205 b0355" id="r0065">Jiang et al., 2014; Wang et al., 2014</ce:cross-refs>). This region has a large amount of exposed soluble carbonate rocks, resulting in poor water retention and soil fertility, as well as discontinuous soil cover (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0095 b0345" id="r0070">Dai et al., 2023; Wang et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). The unique combination of temporary water shortages and extreme microhabitat heterogeneity has led to the coexistence of evergreen and deciduous tree species, creating a distinctive subtropical karst evergreen and deciduous broad-leaved mixed forest. Compared to typical broad-leaved evergreen forest at the same latitude, this type of forest exhibits a richer species composition and a highly diverse ecosystem pattern (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0420 b0395" id="r0075">Zhang et al., 2012; Yang et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Previous studies on plant β-diversity in the karst region have been limited to emphasizing changes in species composition or species richness along altitude. However, how β-diversity contributes to changes in biodiversity patterns during the natural restoration remains unclear. In this study, FDPs were established, and plant community surveys were conducted along the natural restoration of degraded karst forests to address the following questions: (1) What is the relationship between β-diversity and its dependence on turnover or nestedness during the natural restoration of degraded karst forests? (2) Is it niche- or neutral-based processes that determine the community assembly? (3) What is the relative role of soil nutrients and topographic factors on β-diversity?</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st030">Material and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st035">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">This study was conducted in the Maolan National Nature Reserve (107° 52′–108<ce:italic>°</ce:italic> 05′ E, 25<ce:italic>°</ce:italic> 09′–25<ce:italic>°</ce:italic> 20′ N), southwest of China (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0130">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0005"/>). This reserve located in the transitional zone between the Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau and the Guangxi Hilly Plain, with an average elevation of 550 to 850 m. The topography is characterized by higher elevations in the northwest and lower elevations in the southeast. The climate is a subtropical monsoon humid climate, with an average annual temperature of 15.3 °C and an annual precipitation of 1752 mm. Most of the rainfall occurs from April to October, with an average relative humidity of 83 % and an annual average sunshine duration of about 1272.8 h. The parent rocks of the natural reserve are mainly dolomite and limestone, thus forming a unique karst-peaked landscape. Typical karst habitats, characterized by their vulnerability and heterogeneity, exhibit a widespread distribution of bare rocks. Shallow black calcareous soils are interspersed with rocks within the gully, creating a small patch-size spatially heterogeneous habitat. The soil is rich in calcium and organic matter but significantly deficient in phosphorus (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0095 b0385" id="r0080">Dai et al., 2023; Wu et al., 2022c</ce:cross-refs>). Such extreme heterogeneity provides ideal conditions for studying trade-offs in patch size or stress gradients (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0385" id="c0135">Wu et al., 2022c</ce:cross-ref>). Due to poor soils, the dominant vegetation in the study area is evergreen and deciduous broad-leaved mixed forest. Compared to subtropical evergreen broad-leaved forest at the same latitude, it has a more diverse species diversity pattern, with <ce:italic>Quercus glauca</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Clausena dunniana</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Boniodendron minus</ce:italic> as the dominant structures, and <ce:italic>Nandina domestica</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Lindera communis,</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Mahonia fortunei</ce:italic> as the dominant understory species.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st040">Fdps establishment and plant vegetation investigation</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">Currently, rock desertification is one of the most serious environmental issues. Subtropical karst evergreen and deciduous broad-leaved mixed forest is susceptible to biotic and abiotic disturbance that can lead to forest degradation. The main type of disturbance in area was the random selective cutting for firewood harvest. The end of the disturbance indicates that the forest will undergo a process of succession. Degraded karst forests progressively undergo the shrub-canopy mixed forest stage (SC), the secondary-growth forest stage (SG) and eventually return to the old-growth forest stage (OG) (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0140">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). To explore patterns and drivers of β-diversity during natural restoration, a series of FDPs were established along the natural restoration from June to September 2021 following a standard FDP establishment manual (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0080" id="c0145">Condit, 1998</ce:cross-ref>). Ten 30 m × 30 m FDPs were separately established in each stage, with an average distance between FDPs being 2742 m (Tab. S1). In the SC stage, the most recent disturbance occurred 20 years ago (no human disturbance since 2000), and the vegetation colonization was not disturbed. During the SG stage, the same type of anthropogenic disturbance as in the SC stage (random selective cutting) occurred, with the most recent disturbance happened 40 years ago (no human disturbance since 1984). Based on historical evidence and consultation with local elders, there was no human disturbance for at least 100 years in the OG stage. In addition, all restoration stages share the same regional species pool with no anthropogenic disturbance during the natural restoration. In each FDP, all individuals with a diameter at breast height (1.3 m) ≥ 1 cm were marked, measured, and identified to species, with a total of 15,725 marked individuals belonging to 286 species.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st045">Environmental factor acquisition</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0030" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.3.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st050">Soil nutrient factors</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">Soil samples were collected in October 2021 using a five-point sampling method. Firstly, the intersection of the two diagonals of each FDP was taken as the center sampling point, and four points equidistant from the center sampling point along the diagonals were selected as the rest four sampling points. For those sampling points located at exposed rocks, we collected nearby. Then, five soil samples of each FDP were collected at 0–20 cm depth at these locations and mixed evenly to form a composite soil sample. The composite soil samples were air-dried and used for soil nutrient factor determination. A total of four soil nutrient factors were determined, including soil organic carbon (SOC) content, soil available phosphorus (AP) content, soil available potassium (AK) content, and soil available nitrogen (AN) content. The SOC was determined using an elemental analyzer (UNICUBE trace, Elementar, Germany). The soil AP content was determined using the molybdate colorimetry method (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0250" id="c0150">Pansu and Gautheyrou, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). The soil AK content was determined using a velocimeter (TFC-1B, Qiangsheng, China). The soil AN content was determined using the alkaline hydrolysis diffusion method (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0250" id="c0155">Pansu and Gautheyrou, 2006</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0035" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.3.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st055">Topographical factors</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">A handheld LiDAR scanner (SLAM100, FEIMA ROBOTICS, China) was used to capture the point-cloud data of the terrain. Subsequently, the LiDAR360 V6.0 software was employed to compute various terrain parameters. Ground points were distinguished from objects in the handheld LiDAR point-cloud data using the “ground point classification” feature in the software. Then, the extracted ground points were used to generate raster data for the digital elevation model using the function of “digital elevation model” in the software. Finally, based on the digital elevation model raster data, topographic factors, including elevation, slope, profile curvature, and roughness, were calculated using ArcMap 10.8 software.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0040" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st060">Statistical analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0045" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st065">Variations in β-diversity pattern among restoration stages</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">In this study, a multivariate statistical technique, nonmetric multidimensional scaling (NMDS), was employed to characterize species composition among different stages of natural restoration. The Jaccard distance in NMDS was used to measure the difference between samples, and an iterative optimization algorithm was adopted to project the samples into a lower-dimensional space while preserving the original dissimilarity structure as much as possible. The NMDS results were plotted as a scatter diagram, with the distances between points reflecting the difference between samples (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0115" id="c0160">Dexter et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). In order to intuitively describe the inter-group differences along the first and second axes of the NMDS diagram, marginal boxplots were added, and one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) and least significant difference (LSD) multiple comparisons were conducted. Moreover, the uniqueness of the species composition in each FDP was examined by quantifying local contributions to β-diversity (LCBD). The contribution of each FDP to the total variation in species composition was evaluated, indicating the amount of unique species composition occupied by each FDP. To evaluate the total variation in species composition, the total sum of squares (SStotal) of the square-root dissimilarity matrix was quantified by summing the dissimilarities in the triangular matrix and then dividing by the number of observations N. The LCBD was calculated by the following equation (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0215" id="c0165">Legendre and De Cáceres, 2013</ce:cross-ref>):<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="e0005">
                                 <mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">LCBD</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="false">/</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">Total</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>where SS<ce:italic>
                              <ce:inf loc="post">i</ce:inf>
                           </ce:italic> represents the sum of squares corresponding to the <ce:italic>i</ce:italic>th FDP (i.e., the contribution of subplot <ce:italic>i</ce:italic> to the overall β-diversity).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0050" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st070">Decomposition of β-diversity among FDPs of the same restoration stage</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">In this study, the FDPs with lower species richness in our study were strict subsets of FDPs with higher species richness. Therefore, we decomposed the relative contributions of turnover and nestedness β-diversity between FDPs within the same restoration stage to explore the component-dependence of β-diversity during natural restoration processes following the approaches proposed by <ce:cross-ref refid="b0025" id="c0170">Baselga (2010)</ce:cross-ref>. The <ce:italic>β<ce:inf loc="post">turnover</ce:inf>
                           </ce:italic> and <ce:italic>β<ce:inf loc="post">nestedness</ce:inf>
                           </ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0210" id="c0175">Legendre, 2014</ce:cross-ref>) were calculated by the following equations:<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="e0010">
                                 <mml:math altimg="si2.svg">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">turnover</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mfrac>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                             <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi>n</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                             <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mfrac>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>
                           <ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="e0015">
                                 <mml:math altimg="si3.svg">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">nestedness</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mfrac>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo>-</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                             <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>B</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mi>C</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mfrac>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>where <ce:italic>A</ce:italic> represents for the number of species shared between two FDPs; <ce:italic>B</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>C</ce:italic> denote the number of unique species in each FDP.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0055" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st075">The first-order assembly process driving the β-diversity</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">The PER-SIMPER approach (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0160" id="c0180">Gibert and Escarguel (2019</ce:cross-ref>) was adopted to examine the first-order assembly process driving the β-diversity. Three different null distributions could be generated through the PER-SIMPER approach framework in the following ways: 1) reshuffling with a fixed number of rows and constraints; 2) reshuffling with a fixed number of columns and constraints; 3) reshuffling with a fixed number of rows and columns and constraints. These three null distributions represent niche processes, dispersal limitation, and their combined effects on the first-order assembly process, respectively. By comparing the empirical SIMPER profile with three null SIMPER profiles based on the sum of the logarithm of the squared deviations, the first-order assembly process driving the β-diversity was determined. If the distribution of E values for a given null model is significantly lower, the community assembly is dominated by the process corresponding to the null hypothesis. According to <ce:cross-ref refid="b0340" id="c0185">Vilmi et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref>, the dispersal-niche continuum index (DNCI) was calculated based on the E value to assess the relative importance of niche processes and dispersal limitation. A positive DNCI generally reflects the dominance of niche processes, while a negative DNCI indicates a more significant effect of dispersal limitation. With larger absolute values of DNCI, the dominant role of niche or dispersal limitation is stronger.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0060" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.4</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st080">Factors determining variations in β-diversity across restoration stages</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Through variance partitioning analysis (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0045" id="c0190">Borcard et al., 1992</ce:cross-ref>), we quantified the relative importance of soil nutrient factors and topographic factors acting on LCBD, where LCBD was considered the response variable, and the soil nutrient factors and topographical factors were set as explanatory variables. The results were presented in a Venn diagram, effectively illustrating how soil nutrient factors and topographical factors influenced the LCBD (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0225 b0365" id="r0085">López-Delgado et al., 2020; Wu et al., 2021a</ce:cross-refs>). Additionally, a random forest model was employed to further elucidate the main influencing factors on LCBD. Finally, we quantified the influence of dominant topographical factors on LCBD by employing a univariate linear regression based on partial least square method.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">All statistical analyses were performed using the ‘vegan’, ‘adespatial’, ‘ggplot2′, ‘ggpubr’, ‘ggsignif’, ‘randomForest’, ‘rfPermute’, ‘A3′, ‘ggsci’ ‘ggpp’, ‘ggpmisc’ packages and custom function PerSIMPER() in R software version 4.1.0 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0295" id="c0195">R Core Team, 2023</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0065" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st085">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0070" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st090">Variations in β-diversity pattern across natural restoration stages</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">The NMDS results revealed a significant difference in species composition across natural restoration stages (p = 0.001, NMDS stress = 0.1014), indicating that natural restoration dramatically changed the species composition of plant communities (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0200">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0010"/>). Additionally, a similar trend was found in differences in LCBD across natural restoration stages. Our results showed that LCBD was significantly higher in the SC stage than in the OG and SG stages, and the differences between the OG and SG stages were not significant, indicating that the community in the early restoration stage had a unique species composition (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0205">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0015"/>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0075" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st095">Variations in component-dependence of the β-diversity across natural restoration stages</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">The component distribution of β-diversity showed that the differences in species composition were primarily driven by turnover, with contributions of 69.21 %, 73.51 %, and 84.26 % to β-diversity in the SC, SG, and OG stages, respectively. The contribution of nestedness to β-diversity was relatively low, accounting for 30.79 %, 26.49 %, and 15.74 % in the SC, SG, and OG stages, respectively. During the natural restoration, the contribution of turnover to β-diversity showed an increasing trend, while that of nestedness showed a decreasing trend (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0020" id="c0210">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0020"/>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0080" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st100">First-order assembly process driving the β-diversity</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">The E values quantified based on the integrated model were lowest in both the SC-SG stage and the SG-OG stage, indicating that both the neutral and niche processes determined the species composition during natural restoration. However, compared with the niche-based null model, the E values simulated by dispersal-based null distribution were relatively low, indicating that the stochastic factors played a greater role regarding differences in species composition (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0215">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0025"/>b, d). Additionally, the DNCI of the SC-SG stage (−24.801) was much lower than that of the SG-OG stage (−15.492), suggesting a decreasing influence of neutral processes on species composition and an increasing influence of niche processes increased during natural restoration.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0085" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st105">Driving factors determining the β-diversity</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">The variance partitioning analysis revealed that topographic factors were the primary factors influencing β-diversity (total 74 % explanatory ability) in degraded karst forests during natural restoration. Despite the significant effect of soil nutrient factors, the β-diversity was mainly influenced by topographical factors (soil nutrient have only 1 % independent explanatory ability) (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0030" id="c0220">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0030"/>a).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">Further analysis of the random forest model on topographical factors showed that profile curvature was the most significant factor influencing the β-diversity patterns, followed by roughness. Conversely, neither the slope nor the elevation demonstrates a significant impact (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0030" id="c0230">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>b).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">The profile curvature and roughness are both significantly negatively correlated with LCBD, with the negative correlation strength between profile curvature and LCBD being greater than that between roughness and LCBD (profile curvature, <ce:italic>R<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>
                        </ce:italic> = 0.476, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> &lt; 0.001; roughness, <ce:italic>R<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>
                        </ce:italic> = 0.130, <ce:italic>P</ce:italic> = 0.050) (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0035" id="c9000">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0035"/>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0090" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st110">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0095" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st115">Variations in β-diversity and its component-dependence during the natural restoration of degraded karst forests</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">As a key property of forests, β-diversity is closely associated with spatial and temporal changes in biodiversity because it encompasses species formation, extinction, and changes in species distribution (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0040 b0315" id="r0090">Blowes et al., 2019; Seidl et al., 2016</ce:cross-refs>). Similar to the findings of <ce:cross-ref refid="b0150" id="c0235">Geng et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref> in the Helan Mountains, our results also suggested a significant variation in β-diversity during the natural restoration of degraded karst forests. Moreover, the topography of the reserve in this study is complex. A large number of exposed rocks divide habitats into various discontinuous small patches, resulting in severe heterogeneity in environmental factors such as light, heat, and water. As a result, the variations and uncertainty of β-diversity might be exacerbated (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0095 b0345" id="r0095">Dai et al., 2023; Wang et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Continuous specific interactions can constantly change dominant species, ultimately affecting the species composition during the natural restoration, which is the main reason for variations in turnover or nestedness (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0025" id="c0240">Baselga, 2010</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">Different from other succession starting from abandoned farmland, the dominant disturbance type in our study area is the selective cutting of firewood. This disturbance has a slight influence on forests with undamaged propagules but relatively poor soil conditions (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0095 b0345" id="r0100">Dai et al., 2023; Wang et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Once the disturbance stops, both shrubs and canopy trees grow together within local sites to capture the limited light resources. Although the plant community in the early restoration stage is dominated by heliophytes, shade-tolerant trees also coexist with heliophytes (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0015" id="c0245">Anding et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). These less soil-demanding, drought-tolerant, and sunlight-acquiring species are more likely to survive in the early restoration stage, such as <ce:italic>Castanopsis carlesii</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0435" id="c0250">Zhong et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>), <ce:italic>Loropetalum chinense</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0380" id="c0255">Wu et al., 2021b</ce:cross-ref>). With the increase of aboveground biomass during the natural restoration, the growth of canopy trees leads to a severe decrease in understory light conditions (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0410 b0415" id="r0105">Zhang et al., 2010a; Zhang et al., 2020</ce:cross-refs>). As a result, the survival and establishment of heliophytes are significantly limited. Moreover, shade-tolerant trees (e.g., <ce:italic>Acer wangchii</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Cornus parviflora</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Boniodendron minus</ce:italic>) have a light-tolerance advantage and are gradually replacing heliophytes as the dominant species, ultimately changing the species replacement (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0425 b0175" id="r0110">Zhang et al., 2010b; Hanberry, 2019</ce:cross-refs>). Our previous study also suggested that the soil in the study area became more fertile during natural restoration, enabling the growth of soil-demanding species (e.g., <ce:italic>Platycarya strobilacea</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Clausena dunniana</ce:italic>) (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0425" id="c0260">Zhang et al., 2010b</ce:cross-ref>). Normally, the light condition of the climax community is the worst, with shade-tolerant tree species such as <ce:italic>Acer wangchii</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Boniodendron minus</ce:italic> as the dominant species (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0230" id="c0265">Ma et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). The tree heights of heliophytes (<ce:italic>Handeliodendron bodinier</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Pteroceltis tatarinowii</ce:italic>) tend to increase to gain more light or extend their life history range (Tab. S2). Thus, the natural restoration in degraded karst forests positively affects the turnover and nestedness, as well as their relative importance, highlighting the importance of quantifying the components of β-diversity separately.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">The results of partitioning β-diversity suggested that the relative roles of turnover and nestedness changed at different stages of natural restoration. Similar to previous studies (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0055 b0260" id="r0115">Branco et al., 2020; Perez Rocha et al., 2019</ce:cross-refs>), this study also revealed that the changes in β-diversity were mainly driven by turnover, suggesting that turnover has a more significant effect than nestedness on β-diversity patterns during natural restoration in degraded karst forests. Furthermore, the contribution of turnover to β-diversity increased as the natural restoration progressed. The scale differentiation effect of ecological processes might be a possible reason for this trend. Previous studies suggested that the turnover might occur at a smaller local scale because it is associated with habitat filtering or dispersal constraints (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0025 b0030" id="r0120">Baselga, 2010; Baselga, 2012</ce:cross-refs>). At larger local scales, nestedness, which reflected species colonization, was considered to have a greater impact on community structure. (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0270">Cousens et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>). Our results were based on the 30 m grid data, which might fall within the range identified by habitat screening. Diverse microhabitats at local scales in karst landscapes provide more available ecological niche space for species with various ecological strategies. Consequently, there is a high degree of uncertainty in the observed species composition, which might facilitate rapid species replacement (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0110 b0155 b0365" id="r0125">Deák et al., 2021; Gerz et al., 2018; Wu et al., 2021a</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">The high turnover rate between different stages can be attributed to disturbance history. Random selective cutting has been demonstrated to have various impacts on species present. During natural restoration, evolutionary and adaptation strategies of different plants may lead to changes in species composition, resulting in high turnover between every two different sites (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0070 b0375" id="r0130">Chen et al., 2019; Wu et al., 2022b</ce:cross-refs>). Increasing turnover and decreasing nestedness during the natural restoration indicate that the community was approaching a steady state (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0100" id="c0275">Dapporto et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>). The increasing turnover rate throughout the natural restoration process suggested that off-peak climax communities were likely to continue to recover compared to actual peak climax communities. This result was supported by our previous study showing that communities are mainly limited by nitrogen rather than phosphorus (<ce:cross-ref refid="s0125" id="c0280">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>), which was completely different from the situation in subtropical evergreen broad-leaved forest (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0390" id="c0285">Yan et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). Furthermore, species richness almost recovered to pre-disturbance after SG stages (<ce:cross-ref refid="s0125" id="c0290">Fig. S2</ce:cross-ref>). Combined with the high turnover during the natural restoration, the restoration of species composition might require more effort compared with species richness, which was consistent with <ce:cross-ref refid="b0275" id="c0295">Poorter et al. (2016)</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref refid="b0310" id="c0300">Rozendaal et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0100" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st120">First-order assembly process and factors determining the variations in β-diversity</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">The most important divergence between niche and neutral theory concerns which process dominates the community assembly, which is crucial for explaining the changes in species composition during natural restoration (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0290 b0305" id="r0135">Qiao et al., 2015; Rominger et al., 2009</ce:cross-refs>). <ce:cross-ref refid="b0075" id="c0305">Condit et al. (2002)</ce:cross-ref> found that the pure neutral model could effectively fit the β-diversity of tropical tree communities in the Panama Canal. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0105" id="c0310">De Cáceres et al. (2012)</ce:cross-ref> found that the spatial factors determined changes in species composition through dispersal limitation in tropical forests with high biodiversity. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0165" id="c0315">Gilbert et al. (2004)</ce:cross-ref> also found that the effect of niche processes on β-diversity was greater in temperate forests with lower species richness. All these findings suggested that stochastic processes could positively affect species composition in communities with high biodiversity compared with deterministic processes (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0290" id="c0320">Qiao et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). The species richness of subtropical karst evergreen and deciduous broad-leaved mixed forest was high, and their species composition was also driven by stochastic processes. In addition, the large proportion of rare species in our study area could facilitate the examination of stochastic processes (Tab. S2). Because of the small population size, rapid migration rates, and limited geographic range, rare species are considered to be strongly associated with stochastic processes (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0325 b0430" id="r0140">Stanley and Tilman, 2006; Zhang and Zang, 2021</ce:cross-refs>). Therefore, the large number of rare species may be a potential factor contributing to the dominance of stochastic processes in shaping β-diversity patterns.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">This study also showed an increasing number of deterministic processes and a decreasing number of stochastic processes during natural restoration. With changes in light conditions, increases in aboveground biomass and decreases in available resources might further intensify the limiting similarities, thereby affecting the distribution of species abundance (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0350" id="c0325">Wang et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). As a key factor in assessing habitat filtering, soil conditions gradually improved long the natural restoration process, possibly increasing the influence of deterministic processes (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0065 b0290" id="r0145">Chang et al., 2013; Qiao et al., 2015</ce:cross-refs>). Although stochastic processes dominate the natural restoration process, the role of deterministic processes cannot be overlooked. They also play a crucial role in shaping the biodiversity patterns of the karst forests, especially habitat filtering (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0180" id="c0330">He et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The habitat filtering framework primarily shapes species composition mainly through the influences of soil nutrient and topographical factors of microhabitats (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0050 b0180 b0265" id="r0150">Boulangeat et al., 2012; He et al., 2022; Pitman et al., 2001</ce:cross-refs>). Previous studies suggested that topographical factors could indirectly influence the species composition by altering local soil conditions (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0125" id="c0335">Espinosa et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). However, the VPA results of variation partitioning analysis showed that the topographical factors accounted for 47 % of the total variation in LCBD, while soil factors only explained 1 % of the total variation. The combined effect of soil and topographical factors accounted for 27 %, indicating that the direct effect of soil factors on LCBD appeared to be small. Further analysis of random forest modeling suggested that profile curvature and roughness were the most significant topographical factors in determining the variations in LCBD during natural restoration.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Nevertheless, our findings appeared to be inconsistent with previous findings obtained in evergreen and deciduous broad-leaved mixed forest. For instance, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0135" id="c0340">Feng et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref> found that topographical factors influenced the biodiversity pattern primarily by altering soil nutrients in evergreen and deciduous broad-leaved mixed forest of northern subtropics. Moreover, numerous studies have shown that the impact of topography on forest communities is mediated by other factors, such as thermal and hydrological conditions (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0145 b0240 b0285" id="r0155">Fortunel et al., 2018; Moser et al., 2009; Punchi-Manage et al., 2013</ce:cross-refs>). This study was conducted in an extremely heterogeneous forest ecosystem, where a large number of exposed rocks fragmented the habitat into many small patches of different sizes. When performing a relative study at a given plot scale, these patches might directly influence the plant diversity pattern.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">The growth and development of plants in karst forests were influenced by the spatial discontinuity rather than the soil nutrient values. In previous studies, soil nutrients in karst forests did not show a significantly lower pattern than other vegetation types at the same latitude (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0445 b0330" id="r0160">Zhu et al., 2021; Sun et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Additionally, this spatial discontinuity works well at established plot scales. In this study, soils were sparse on rock surfaces or platforms, and sampling in rock crevices and gullies was difficult. As a result, obtaining soil samples that could adequately represent the overall soil nutrient status of the study site was challenging. Furthermore, the increase in surface fluctuation may be associated with a decrease in soil thickness, consequently influencing the role of soil factors (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0345">Fortunel et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). The results indicated that topographic factors had a significant impact on LCBD, with profile curvature and roughness having the greatest influence, and LCBD decreased as their increase. This suggested that the β-diversity pattern in karst forests was largely influenced by microhabitat heterogeneity. Profile curvature and roughness respectively represented the terrain's undulation and irregularity. On the one hand, rugged terrain provided a variety of microhabitats, enhancing habitat heterogeneity and favoring resource utilization (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0135" id="c0350">Feng et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). On the other hand, excessively high profile curvature and roughness in some areas may lead to small habitat patches, limiting plant colonization and development, thereby affecting community β-diversity (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0130" id="c0355">Fahrig, 2003</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0105" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st125">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">By comparing the β-diversity and its components, this study demonstrated that the species composition changed significantly during the natural restoration of degraded karst forests, and the species turnover dominated the variations in β-diversity. Despite the significant influence of stochastic processes on the β-diversity in karst forests, the influence of deterministic processes exhibited an increasing trend during the natural restoration of degraded karst forests. Profile curvature and roughness were the more important factor influencing the β-diversity than soil nutrients, and LCBD significantly decreased with their increase. This study highlighted that the natural restoration of species composition required more effort than species richness. Distinguishing various components of biodiversity could well facilitate biodiversity conservation, forest management, and regional environmental management.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0110" view="all">
